 historians over the past twenty years. The chapters that follow showcase the work of new and established scholars who draw on critical race theory, postcolonial theory, and transnational history to re-examine familiar topics such as biography and oral history, paid and unpaid work, marriage and family, and women's political action. Whether they focus on the marriage of Governor James Douglas and his Metis wife, Amelia, or on the experiences of Q�b�cois domestic workers in the 1970s, the contributors demonstrate the continued relevance of history informed by feminist perspectives and open a much-needed dialogue between francophone and anglophone historians in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismzCanadaxHistory. 0aWomenzCanadavBiography. 0aWomenzCanadaxHistory. 0aWomenzCanadaxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aBalcom, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelisle, Donica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Gail G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarstairs, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarstairs, Catherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCharron, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharron, Hélène, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFine-Meyer, Rose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGidney, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHampton, Anthony S. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeap, Ruby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanovicek